# Product docs vs design docs

## Read the PDR first (product, data, features)

For tasks that involve **any** of the following, read the relevant sections of `docs/EduAI_PDR_v3_0.md` (or `@`-reference it in chat) **before** implementing:

- Database: schema, migrations, queries, RLS, data modeling
- **Building functionality or features**: product behavior, flows, requirements, acceptance criteria, domain rules
- Backend/API behavior tied to product requirements

If the PDR does not cover the topic, say so and proceed from code and existing patterns.

## Do not use the PDR for design-only tasks

If the task is **purely design or visual**—for example typography, spacing, color tokens, component styling, layout polish, motion, or design-system compliance—with **no** change to product behavior, data model, or feature requirements, **do not** treat `docs/EduAI_PDR_v3_0.md` as the source of truth.

## Design-only tasks: use these instead

For design work, follow:

- `.cursor/rules/design-system.mdc` (project design tokens and UI rules)
- `.agents/skills/ui-craft/references/supabase-design-system.md` (deeper reference)

## Mixed tasks (feature + UI)

When building a feature that includes UI: use the **PDR** for what to build and how it should behave; use the **design-system** references above for how it should look and feel.
